    id: "9176bbc5-8346-4593-b79b-14b20fa8fdaf",
    description: `Majmu al-Fatawa — Selected Volumes brings together a carefully curated collection of religious rulings and scholarly opinions from the incomparable works of Shaykh al-Islam Ibn Taymiyyah (661–728 AH), one of the most influential Islamic jurists, theologians, and thinkers in the history of Islam. This selection from his larger compendium of fatawa covers an extraordinary range of topics including Islamic creed (Aqeedah), jurisprudence (Fiqh) across all four major schools of thought, Quranic exegesis (Tafsir), Hadith methodology, spiritual purification, and contemporary issues of his era that remain remarkably relevant today. Ibn Taymiyyah's approach to issuing fatawa was distinguished by his direct reliance on the Quran and authentic Sunnah, his deep knowledge of the Arabic language, and his willingness to challenge scholarly consensus when he found stronger evidence from primary sources.

The selected volumes included in this collection cover key areas of Islamic practice and belief. Readers will find detailed discussions on the correct understanding of Allah's names and attributes, the proper methodology for deriving Islamic rulings, the categorization of Tawheed into its three components, detailed rulings on Salah, Zakat, fasting, and Hajj, comprehensive guidance on financial transactions and business ethics, and thorough examinations of innovations (Bid'ah) in religious practice. Ibn Taymiyyah's fatawa on social issues — including family disputes, inheritance, and community relations — demonstrate his practical wisdom and deep understanding of human nature. His responses to questions about spiritual diseases such as arrogance, envy, and ostentation provide readers with a framework for self-purification that remains among the most sophisticated in Islamic literature.

What distinguishes this collection is Ibn Taymiyyah's unique ability to synthesize information from multiple Islamic disciplines into coherent, actionable guidance. His fatawa frequently draw connections between theology and jurisprudence, showing how correct belief naturally leads to correct practice. The selected volumes include his famous rulings on the permissibility of certain contemporary practices, his refutations of philosophical positions that contradicted Islamic orthodoxy, and his detailed discussions on the methodology of the early generations of Muslims (Salaf al-Salih). Each fatwa is presented with its full chain of reasoning, the evidence upon which it is based, and responses to counter-arguments, allowing readers to understand not just the ruling but the scholarly process behind it. This selection makes Ibn Taymiyyah's vast scholarship accessible to readers who might be intimidated by the complete multi-volume Majmu al-Fatawa, which runs to over thirty volumes in its fullest printed edition. The text includes extensive scholarly annotations and cross-references to Ibn Taymiyyah's other major works.`
