    id: "83b95e94-cf5b-4322-8a8d-c658a5b8d6af",
    description: `Riyad us-Saliheen — Gardens of the Righteous is the most widely read Hadith collection in the Muslim world after the six canonical (Kutub al-Sittah), compiled by the towering scholar Imam Yahya ibn Sharaf al-Nawawi (631–676 AH). This masterpiece of Islamic literature organizes approximately 1,896 authentic Hadith into 372 chapters covering every conceivable aspect of a Muslim's daily life — from the fundamentals of faith and purification, through prayer, fasting, charity, and pilgrimage, to social etiquette, business dealings, family relations, and the remembrance of Allah. Imam Nawawi selected these Hadith primarily from Sahih al-Bukhari and Sahih Muslim, supplementing with narrations from Abu Dawud, at-Tirmidhi, an-Nasai, and Ibn Majah, ensuring that every Hadith in this collection meets the highest standards of authentication.

The organizational structure of Riyad us-Saliheen reflects Imam Nawawi's genius for making Islamic knowledge accessible and practical. The book is divided into twenty main sections that progressively guide the reader from the foundations of faith through worship, character refinement, and social responsibilities. Section one covers the virtues of good intentions, patience, and repentance. Subsequent sections address the obligations of Salah and its spiritual dimensions, the etiquettes of fasting and Ramadan, the rules and wisdom of Zakat, and the comprehensive guidance for Hajj and Umrah. Later sections delve into the Prophetic manners of eating, drinking, sleeping, dressing, and greeting others, while the final sections focus on the remembrance of Allah, supplication, and preparation for the afterlife. Each Hadith is accompanied by its source and chain of narration, and many include Imam Nawawi's brief explanatory notes that clarify ambiguous phrases or contextualize the narration.

The enduring popularity of Riyad us-Saliheen stems from its practical orientation — unlike many Hadith collections that serve primarily as references for scholars, this work was designed for daily use by ordinary Muslims seeking to implement the Sunnah in their everyday lives. The brief, focused chapters make it ideal for reading one or two selections per day, and many families use it as a daily reading companion after Fajr or Maghrib prayers. Islamic scholars worldwide have written commentaries on this work, the most famous being the multi-volume commentary by Imam Muhammad ibn Allan as-Siddiqi al-Bakri. The book has been translated into virtually every major language and serves as a cornerstone of Islamic education curricula from primary schools through university level. Whether used for systematic study, daily spiritual nourishment, or as a reference for specific life situations, Riyad us-Saliheen remains an indispensable companion for every Muslim household.`
