    id: "4b4af396-658b-4d48-9c15-2ac0b1e4eadb",
    description: `Fortress of the Muslim (Hisnul Muslim) - Duas Collection is the most comprehensive and widely referenced compilation of daily supplications (Azkar and Adhkar) from the authentic Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). Originally compiled by the Saudi scholar Sa'id ibn Ali ibn Wahf al-Qahtani, this indispensable pocket-sized reference contains over 260 verified supplications covering virtually every situation a Muslim encounters in daily life — from waking and sleeping, through entering and leaving the mosque, before and after eating, during travel, at times of distress, and in moments of gratitude and celebration. Each supplication is presented with its complete Arabic text, transliteration for non-Arabic speakers, English translation, and detailed source references from the primary Hadith collections.

The organization of Hisnul Muslim follows the natural rhythm of a Muslim's day and the various circumstances of life. The book opens with supplications for the morning and evening (Adhkar as-Sabah wal-Masa'), which the Prophet described as a fortress protecting the believer throughout the day. Subsequent sections cover supplications for prayer — including the opening invocation (Du'a al-Istiftah), the recitations during Ruku and Sujud, and the supplications of Qunut and Tashahhud. Comprehensive sections address supplications for eating and drinking, wearing new clothes, using the restroom, entering and leaving the home, traveling by various means, visiting the sick, attending funerals, and seeking refuge from various spiritual and physical harms. The collection includes the famous supplications of the Prophets found in the Quran and authentic Sunnah, giving readers access to the exact words used by Prophets including Adam, Ibrahim, Musa, Isa, and Muhammad (peace be upon them all) when calling upon their Lord.

A distinguishing feature of this collection is the compiler's meticulous attention to authenticity. Sa'id al-Qahtani carefully verified every supplication against the major Hadith collections, grading each narration's authenticity and providing its source with volume, book, and Hadith number. Supplications whose chains of narration are weak or fabricated have been excluded, giving readers confidence that every dua in this book is reliable and acceptable to Allah. The book includes a detailed introduction explaining the virtues and etiquettes of making dua, the optimal times when supplications are more likely to be accepted, the factors that prevent dua from being answered, and the common mistakes people make when supplicating. Footnotes throughout provide contextual explanations for unfamiliar Arabic terms, clarify the occasions on which specific supplications were taught by the Prophet, and offer practical guidance on incorporating these Azkar into one's daily routine. This book has become the standard dua reference in mosques, Islamic schools, and Muslim households worldwide.`
