    id: "648c8096-e21a-477a-a009-4a6d3948add1",
    description: `13 Lines Quran Parah 11 to 15 is a set of five individual Paras (Juz) of the Holy Quran printed in the traditional South Asian 13-line format that has been the standard for Quran publication in the subcontinent for generations. This set covers Paras 11 through 15, corresponding to Surah At-Tawbah (from its final verses) through portions of Surah An-Nahl, encompassing some of the most profoundly significant passages of the Quran including the concluding verses of Surah At-Tawbah, the complete Surahs of Yunus, Hud, Yusuf, Ar-Ra'd, and Ibrahim, and the opening sections of Surah Al-Hijr. Each Para is bound as a separate soft-cover booklet, making it convenient for students, Hafiz candidates, and daily readers to carry and study specific portions of the Quran without handling the complete Mushaf.

The 13-line format follows the standard South Asian pagination where each page contains exactly 13 lines of Quranic text, with consistent placement of verses across all editions published in this format. This consistency is critically important for Hafiz students who memorize not only the words of the Quran but also the visual layout of each page, allowing them to recall the exact position of each verse during revision and examination. The text is printed in clear, well-spaced Naskh script that is recognized for its readability and aesthetic beauty, with full vowel marks (Tashkeel) and Tajweed color-coding on selected editions to aid proper pronunciation. The Arabic text is sufficiently large for comfortable reading during both individual study and congregational settings.

This particular set (Paras 11-15) contains several sections that are especially important for Islamic study. Surah Yusuf (contained in Para 12-13) is the most detailed narrative of any Prophet in the Quran, providing lessons in patience, family dynamics, dream interpretation, and divine providence. Surah Ibrahim (in Para 13) presents powerful arguments for monotheism. Surah At-Tawbah (completing in Para 11) contains fundamental rulings on jihad, treaties with non-Muslims, and the duty of enjoining good and forbidding evil. The individual Para format makes these sets extremely practical for Islamic school classrooms where students are assigned specific Paras to study, for Hafiz circles where memorization is done one Para at a time, and for new Muslims who may find the complete Quran overwhelming and prefer to begin with manageable portions. Each Para booklet in this set is printed on quality paper with durable binding designed to withstand frequent handling.`
