    id: "3e6fea37-45ea-4377-a9f4-5dee6956accc",
    description: `13 Lines Quran Parah 6 to 10 is a set of five individual Paras (Juz) of the Holy Quran in the traditional South Asian 13-line format, covering Paras 6 through 10 which contain some of the most theologically rich and legally significant Surahs of the Quran. This portion of the Quran includes the completion of Surah Al-Ma'idah, the complete Surahs of Al-An'am, Al-A'raf, Al-Anfal, and At-Tawbah, as well as the beginning of Surah Yunus. These Surahs address foundational themes of Islamic belief including the oneness of Allah, the stories of previous Prophets, the establishment of Islamic law, the ethics of warfare, and the relationship between Muslims and people of other faiths. Each Para is produced as a separate booklet with soft binding for easy individual handling.

Surah Al-An'am (Para 7-8) stands out as one of the longest and most comprehensive Surahs addressing Tawheed (the oneness of God), presenting detailed arguments for the existence and unity of the Creator through natural signs, prophetic evidence, and rational discourse. Surah Al-A'raf (Para 8-9) contains the detailed accounts of Adam and Hawwa, Nuh, Hud, Salih, Lut, Shu'ayb, and Musa (peace be upon them all), providing some of the most vivid prophetic narratives in the entire Quran. Surah At-Tawbah (Para 10-11) is the only Surah in the Quran that does not begin with the Basmalah, containing instead stern warnings and critical rulings on the treatment of hypocrites, polytheists, and the obligations of Muslims in matters of collective defense and social justice.

The 13-line format used in this edition maintains the exact same page layout as the complete 13-line Mushaf, meaning students who memorize from these individual Paras can seamlessly transition to reading from the full Quran without any disruption to their visual memory. This consistency is the primary reason madrasas and Hafiz schools across Pakistan, India, Bangladesh, and the diaspora prefer the 13-line format. The text is printed in clear Naskh script with full vowelization (I'rab), making it suitable for readers at all levels from beginners to advanced scholars. The individual Para format offers significant practical advantages — students can focus on one portion at a time, teachers can distribute specific Paras to class members, and the booklets are lightweight enough to carry in a bag or keep at one's bedside. This set (Paras 6-10) is printed on opaque, durable paper that prevents show-through from the reverse side, ensuring comfortable reading in all lighting conditions.`
